25|$|Thirty-six U.S. states (and the District of Columbia) also {{recognize}} an <b>implied</b> <b>contract</b> {{as an exception}} to at-will employment.|$|E
25|$|Most {{states have}} {{modified}} {{the general rule}} that employment is at will by holding that employees may, under that state's common law, have <b>implied</b> <b>contract</b> rights to fair treatment by their employers. US private-sector employees thus {{do not have the}} indefinite contracts (similar to US academic tenure) traditionally common in many European countries, Canada and New Zealand.|$|E
25|$|Where an {{individual}} is contracted to perform certain duties, a {{failure to do so}} may result in criminal liability. The principle of liability arising from a mutual agreement arose from the decision of R v Instan, where a woman was found guilty of manslaughter, after failing to summon medical attention for her aunt, who maintained them both. The decisions of the court suggest that an <b>implied</b> <b>contract</b> of mutual benefit existed, so as to imply a duty upon the defendant to act. As demonstrated by 'R v Pittwood (1902), where a gatekeeper was found criminally liable for failing to perform his duties correctly, this principle may be extended to instances where the injured individual is a third party.|$|E
